@rmflight @thosjleeper @rOpenSci @Hadley As I recall we got around this by ensuring the @test directive was strictly additive and would not clobber existing non-@test tests, which at the time we thought/hoped was sufficient but may warrant some more thought.
If anyone has a more formal or practical way of doing this with the current level of knowledge, I'd be interested to hear their opinions 5/
Until we have something more solid, however, we need to weigh the results _roughly_ by individual evaluations of how good the FFs perform in a series of tests across many systems 4/

More recently, this has started to become a lot more serious - e.g. with the @openforcefield initiative. While we are still far away from a useful distribution of a protein force field, I still think there is real scientific merit to sample FFs 3/

Already some time ago @AndersRNorgaard, @BorgFerkinghoff and I started playing around with Bayesian methods for FF parameterization (against experimental data), though we ended up using max-likelihood estimators in practice 2/ https://t.co/iocf8WnR3G

In the future I expect that we will integrate out FF noise in a fully Bayesian fashion, so running multiple simulations with a distribution of FFs will not only be convenient, but in fact the right thing to do 1/ https://t.co/hL8cuHtRJ8

As always, we'd be delighted to hear feedback - comment on the preprint or email/tweet us with any thoughts!

We finish with a set of broad guidelines for anyone considering assessing candidate drug targets with human LoF variants. While a lot of this is common sense, we've found that many of these steps are ignored or minimized in current practice. https://t.co/aeCDjZWFYn

A final lesson from the paper is the critical need for careful curation of candidate LoF variants before pursuing expensive follow-up. These variants are highly enriched for artifacts, especially the common ones (look at MAPT and HTT in this table!). https://t.co/bYSeTNz5YQ

The overall message is that a bottlenecked population will increase the frequency of homozgous LoF for a subset of genes, but if you really want to find knockouts you need to be looking in consanguineous populations. This is why I'm so excited about @EastLondonGenes.

In this plot, Eric compares an outbred population (top) with a bottlenecked population like Finland (middle), and a population with a high level of consanguinity i.e. parental relatedness (bottom). Heterozygous LoF in orange, homozygous "knockouts" in purple. https://t.co/W8htpYumva

Turns out simply looking at ever larger numbers in outbred European populations won't do - for many genes, we likely won't see a knockout even if we sequence everyone on Earth. Our only hope is looking at populations with demographic properties that make knockouts more likely.

Where LoF variants become really powerful is in finding individuals who DO carry such variants, and assessing their phenotype. Ideally, we'd like to be able to find human "knockouts" (both copies inactivated) for all human genes. But how could we do so?

The answer is: it's complicated. Successful drug targets are, in aggregate, slightly *more* constrained than other genes, but there's no clear correlation between constraint and on-target safety. This makes sense given many biological confounders, which we lay out in the paper. https://t.co/ygvmPrfWUl

This paper is an attempt to lay the foundations for such a framework. The first question is what we can learn from the degree to which genes are depleted for LoF variants (so-called LoF constraint). Are successful drug targets more or less constrained than other genes?

This paper grew from the work Eric described in this blog post: https://t.co/XUiMSZ3z6J Basically, over the last few years we've talked to many pharma scientists keen to include LoF variants in target validation, but without a clear conceptual framework for doing so.

So, over the next month we're posting gnomAD companion preprints (see https://t.co/dGR8ApmwE7). Here's the first of those, a data-driven perspective piece led by @cureffi focused on using human loss-of-function variants to assess candidate drug targets: https://t.co/8hmZttHsyb

"to reduce the amount of irreproducible and flawed science, allowing the formal citation of online postings will require that their quality is also assessed during peer review"In my field, it's rare that any new data/method/etc we present is so heavily reliant on a citation.
"Formal citation of a preprint elevates that work to a position that appears equivalent to a peer-reviewed published article." Maybe in some fields, but in mine that is rarely the case.

"over-reliance on unreviewed material can result in negative evaluation of the manuscript under consideration at NAR."Wow, that's heavy handed. We as editors don't really like preprints, so we may reject your paper if you cite too many.

"The formal citation of any research is a serious responsibility for any author and has the effect of validating that article‚Äôs contents and conclusions."That's a bit extreme. In my field, it does has the effect of saying somebody did something (interesting, usually).

Microbiomes from diverse non-Westernized populations (incl. newly sequenced Madagascar population) contain many species and subspecies without previous genomes or isolates that are prevalent but only occasionally detectable in the microbiomes from Westernized populations. 4/5

Many of the new candidate species (SGBs) are unexplored (uSGBs). 10 uSGBs among the 100 most prevalent ("assemblable") species. Newly named "Candidatus Cibiobacter qucibialis" revealed by >1,800 assembled genomes is placed between Ruminococcus and Faecalibacterium. 3/5

New genomes increase the mappability of gut metagenomes to an avg >87% median >94%. Similar improvement for oral microbiomes. Close to have a quite complete picture of the bacterial+archaeal diversity of the human microbiome across populations, but need more euks and viruses! 2/5

Here is what we found: by single-sample strictly QC'ed metagenomic assembly we reconstructed over 154,000 genomes from 9,428 metagenomes representing the global multi-bodysite human microbime. The genomes were recapitulated in a total of 4,930 species-level genome bins (SGBs) 1/5

Whatever happens the 29th won‚Äôt be the end; it will - sadly - be just the next phase. And ... as proud Brit (harder to say these days) and a committed European (whatever the result) I will work hard for an open Britain, working with colleagues across Europe.
But ... if Parliament can find a majority for a resolution that would be better. In fact, banning referenda in the future might well be sensible
I get a second referendum may well vote out still ; at least this is with better knowledge of the outcome.
(Yes this reality might have been different if different choices were made - be it a Labour Government or an ERG driven Government - but that‚Äôs not the reality we are in now)

Exiting the EU was always a more cultural and domestic political project (or windmill ) than a coherent plan; I think it is credible - sensible - for Parliament to return to ask the electorate again now the reality is clearer

I‚Äôm glad that Parliament has now more influence - with a Government without an effective majority something closer to a free vote is a reasonable way forward. That said this is ultimately a negotiation with with another government (and ... far more coherent than ours)

British news (politics) is ... messy, depressing, almost too depressing in its pettiness, posturing with an unhealthy dose of very nasty intimidation. That said, at least (some of) the arguments are circling in on the substantive issue - what will happen on the 29th march.

Also, what metric do you use to say that the set of filters chosen is adequate? I think this is important in processing sequence data, but not discussed a lot. So, any thoughts would be appreciated! I would love to learn more!
In previous projects, I've used depth (DP) and the proportion of being genotypes across all samples (AN). 1000G strictmask uses total coverage and mapping quality.

In the end though, smart people on both sides will always tell you to use both: in machine learning as a baseline for your other models, in stats to guard against incorrect assumptions, model misspecification etc.

Additionally, always remember that good old least squares estimators are consistent under more general conditions than logistic estimators. Logistic suffers and is biased under varying variances aka heteroskedasticity conditions.

This post summarizes things pretty well. General takeaway points are: (1) logistic assumes a specific form for the probabilities, these are not minimal assumptions (2) odds ratios (how you interpret logistic) are harder to interpret than you think  https://t.co/yXil2h1ozY

So it's no wonder when that when you talk to folks in machine learning, they vouch for logistic, whereas stats focused like linear better. One is trained to be focused on the response, the other on the coefficients.

I think the split is mainly due to the difference of focus of in modeling. If you are interested in modeling the response and need the response to be in form of probabilities, logistic is a good choice. If you are interesting in interpreting the *effect size*, then use linear

5/5 stoicism is more of a personal discipline, a method for achieving one‚Äôs goals, but not a way of determining which ultimate goals are worthy to pursue. for that, something larger is required.

4/5 two more virtues one might pursue sovereignty: establishment and retention of control over one‚Äôs life transcendence: perceiving the game we‚Äôre in and attempting to find out which game that game is situated within, etc., ad infinitum.

3/5 pursuit of virtue can encompass individual greatness if the virtues pursued demand such greatness. so if we can define some additional virtues that capture individual greatness, or define the existing ones in those terms, stoicism may still be of use.
2/5 stoicism demands the pursuit of virtue. the cardinal virtues are wisdom, courage, temperance, and justice. probing further, the meaning ‚Äúwisdom‚Äù is defined circularly as ‚Äúright reason‚Äù.

The professionals (I am not one; I am downstream user) can point out the host of gotchas about these schemes - training/testing bleed through, performance assessments, over-training/inability to generalise. But, nevertheless, biology - we have a serious new power tool!

(And of course lots of people are using deep neural networks now in biology - from image recognition through to nanopore sequencing to protein folding through to genomic functional interpretation - but I think there is serious headroom and way more potential)

Biology has *a lot* to gain from this because we have insanely complex, baroque machines (life) we are trying to model, which obviously obey the laws of physics but generate very non obvious outputs from the precise set up of these machines

It is ... so simple. Just do it.

Plenty of studies go to "it's genome wide, there are enough variants/CRISPR hits/whatever with an effect size that will give me a result" - this is fine - in which case, just a sentence or two for how you control false discovery would be nice.

Putting in a power calculation is no guarantee you will find stuff (you can *always* fudge the parameters) but it shows you have been honest *at least with yourself* about just how far from reality the parameters have to be for you to get a result.

I'm in review mode, and just a reminder for all people writing grants with a statistical bit, just put in at least one sentence about the power calculation; even if the power calculation is basically "group XX did a similar study with similar sample size and got a result"

In the end, this sounds an awful lot like a farm. The difference is I dont really expect or need it to be a money making venture. For some projects, I need most of the plants to die. You can't expect to make money with that plan.Maybe a, "research farm" better fits my goal.

If nothing comes of them? Well, I didn't spend much of any money or effort on them anyhow.(There are even agricultural research grants I could apply for from the state to help support some of this style project, but I'd have to get things started to show I can do them.)

I also want space for more experimental projects. Lavender and Rosemary are borderline plants here. Winter kills them.The plan? Plant out bulk seed for each and then watch the vast majority of them die over the next few winters. Then, save seeds from those & try again.

I also want space for growing out more tomatoes, pepper, & tomatillos from my breeding projects. More plants let's me select through more genetic recombinations faster. Right now I can grow a few from each line in each year and slowly crawl towards my goals for them.

Goal for 2019. Start a farm. (No, not really.)I do want to scale up my gardening activities. I like the idea of growing all that we need for the year of some crop.I need more space for garlic, onions, & dry beans. They store well, so we can eat from them for much of the year.
